Semilarski against prosecutors: the cassation of the former vice-mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances to consider the claim of Semilarski refused, but in April his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On December 12, 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, since her permission is not within his competence of the administrative court.
The court order stated that the complaint contained a claim for damage caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the county court should regulate such issues,” Anett Kreitsmann, spokeswoman for the Tartu Courts, told ERR.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the State Court will have to say its word.
According to the defender of Semilarski, a jury Oliver Nyaez, his client for about two years unreasonably was under suspicion of bribery.
Now he demands from the prosecutor's office to refute the wrong allegations in his address and compensate him for moral damages.
The reason for filing a complaint with the court was the statements of the prosecutor for special cases of the Lyuna district prosecutor’s office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, along with another Deputy Mayor of Tartu Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“Recall that when I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu – one of the most influential bodies of local government – are corrupt.
These public suspicions hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now, when these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to talk about it,” Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nääs, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The claim of bribery and venal turned out to be false, but this is not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as in Lithuania, that at the investigative stage, state representatives should be careful when choosing words so that the suspects would not be represented as criminals before sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is also obliged to do so with the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not respected in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Nääs said.
“The public submission of Semilarski as a serious offender and bribe-taker in circumstances where the facts underlying suspicion of bribery are still being clarified is unacceptable, which is contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfairly against the applicant,” the lawyer added.
As rus.err.ee wrote, the former vice-mayor of Tartu, Valvo Semilarski, will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him was partially closed against him in July.
At the same time, the former official is tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated in the meetings of the city government more than thirty times in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or leaders of which Semilarski actively communicated at the personal level outside of the time.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to distance himself from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor’s office presented Semilarski suspected of receiving a bribe and violating the anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
Then the prosecutor’s office and the Security Police said that there was strong evidence against both vice-mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
The Suvorov case later reached the court, which fully acquitted the politician.
The trial of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
