How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia expectedly again reduced the key rate.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage points, to 4.25% per annum - formally another historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short step of the rate cut, as well as the tone of the statements of the Central Bank and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistically than before.
This means that the current cycle of easing monetary policy may soon stop.
“We continued to ease monetary policy, primarily taking into account that the risks of inflation deviations down from 4% in 2021 still remain,” said the head of the Bank of Russia Elvira Nabiullina.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a drop in domestic and external demand.
The recovery of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods were restored, the annual rate of decrease in cargo turnover and industrial production slowed down.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the contraction of the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (before that, 4-6% was expected), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $ 40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the Central Bank expected 27 and 35 dollars per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s forecast for inflation for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to economists for Russia and the CIS "Renaissance Capital" Sofia Donets and Andrei Melashchenko.
So, the Bank of Russia has consistently lowered the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already dropped by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it by one percentage point due to the low rate of inflation due to the suppressed demand and the need to stimulate the economy that has stirred due to the pandemic and the associated restrictions.
The chances of conding of monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The set of pro-inflationary risks also indicates the proximity of the pause in easing interest policy - disrupted supply chains, a possible increase in costs due to measures to prevent the epidemic and a faster (compared to expectations) recovery in demand, he says.
To top up the subsequent actions of the Bank of Russia will require more attention to inflation processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
One way or another, the reduction of the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, possibly, by the mortgage, senior economist of the analytical department of the Bank “Opening” Maxim Petronevich.
Correction of rates will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
Rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates can end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, the economist of BCS Premier Anton Pokatovich does not exclude.
Average interest rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they can fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
Further, they can fall to 4%, if the Central Bank reduces the key rate in the fall, says Pokatovich.
